00:04:49.869 --> 00:04:50.410
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:04:50.410 --> 00:04:51.119
How old were you?

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:52.160
JOYCE CHITTICK: I was 17.

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:52.810
SPEAKER: Wow.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:55.000
JOYCE CHITTICK: I finished
high school on the road

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.540
by correspondence the
days before computers.

00:04:58.540 --> 00:04:59.920
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:00.420
Yes.

00:05:00.420 --> 00:05:02.290
That's how old I am.

00:05:02.290 --> 00:05:03.730
So there was no laptop.

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:05.500
I hand wrote all of my papers.

00:05:05.500 --> 00:05:09.310
And then I would save
them up, and then

00:05:09.310 --> 00:05:11.650
I would put them in
a FedEx envelope,

00:05:11.650 --> 00:05:13.450
and I'd send them to my teacher.

00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:16.630
And my dad, I remember one
time, because it'd been a while

00:05:16.630 --> 00:05:19.120
since I'd sent anything.

00:05:19.120 --> 00:05:22.360
He wasn't sure that I
was doing my homework

00:05:22.360 --> 00:05:26.020
because I was saving them up
to send them in one big FedEx.

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:30.220
And it was on that tour that
I met Kathleen Marshall, whom

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:31.780
I've done a lot of shows with.

00:05:31.780 --> 00:05:35.620
And so as far as
women go, Kathleen

00:05:35.620 --> 00:05:41.230
has been very instrumental in
giving me many opportunities

00:05:41.230 --> 00:05:43.790
in this Broadway career.

00:05:43.790 --> 00:05:48.310
And just like Melissa just said,
since the time I was little,

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:52.210
this was my dream, Broadway.

00:05:52.210 --> 00:05:54.670
I remember seeing a Tony
Awards when I was, like,

00:05:54.670 --> 00:05:56.280
seven or eight years old.

00:05:56.280 --> 00:05:58.155
But that was the only
time you could watch it

00:05:58.155 --> 00:06:01.530
because you couldn't rewind,
and you couldn't YouTube it.

00:06:01.530 --> 00:06:05.170
And that image of
those Tony Awards

00:06:05.170 --> 00:06:08.590
stuck with me till the next
year when they were on TV.

00:06:08.590 --> 00:06:13.097
And it was always my dream goal.

00:06:13.097 --> 00:06:15.430
SPEAKER: Stacey, can you tell
us about your career path?

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:16.263
STACEY ZALOGA: Yeah.

00:06:16.263 --> 00:06:20.440
I actually got into theater
and this whole aspect

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:22.660
of entertainment later
than most people.

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:23.860
It wasn't until college.

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:26.590
I was on a totally
different career path.

00:06:26.590 --> 00:06:31.180
And my second year of
college is when I kind of

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:32.962
had my quarter-life
crisis and decided

00:06:32.962 --> 00:06:34.420
to completely change
what I thought

00:06:34.420 --> 00:06:36.550
I wanted to do my whole life.

00:06:36.550 --> 00:06:38.355
SPEAKER: What was
your original plan?

00:06:38.355 --> 00:06:40.480
STACEY ZALOGA: I thought
I was going to be pre-med.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.360
And I was following my
dad's footsteps at that time

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:48.730
and wanted to be a doctor, or
so I thought, since I was nine.

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:50.110
And then I got to college.

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:52.650
And it wasn't going the way
I thought it was going to go.

00:06:52.650 --> 00:06:56.860
And I decided to
take four classes

00:06:56.860 --> 00:06:58.930
my second year of
college in anything

00:06:58.930 --> 00:07:00.520
that I was remotely
interested in.

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:03.220
And an introductory to
theater class was one of them

00:07:03.220 --> 00:07:05.861
because my parents had always
brought me to New York.

00:07:05.861 --> 00:07:08.110
They're from New York
originally and would bring me in

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:09.070
to see Broadway shows.

00:07:09.070 --> 00:07:11.762
And I fell in love with
it at an early age,

00:07:11.762 --> 00:07:13.720
but I never, in a million
years, thought that I

00:07:13.720 --> 00:07:17.620
would have a career in it.

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:20.320
So the introductory to
theater was just on a whim.

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:24.550
And I fell in love with it,
and ended up changing schools

00:07:24.550 --> 00:07:26.320
and changing majors.

00:07:26.320 --> 00:07:28.840
So by my third year college,
that's when I first started.

00:07:28.840 --> 00:07:31.420
And I didn't even know
what a stage manager was.

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:35.050
I went to the
University of Kentucky.

00:07:35.050 --> 00:07:36.629
And I went to the
theater department.

00:07:36.629 --> 00:07:38.170
And they were like,
why are you here?

00:07:38.170 --> 00:07:40.870
And I was like, well,
you know how you

00:07:40.870 --> 00:07:43.320
watch the making of a movie?

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:45.910
I'm obsessed with that,
like, the behind the scenes,

00:07:45.910 --> 00:07:46.450
whatever.

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:49.007
And one of my professors
said, on that very first day

00:07:49.007 --> 00:07:51.340
when I met him, he said, you'd
be a great stage manager.

00:07:51.340 --> 00:07:52.780
And I was like, what's that?

00:07:52.780 --> 00:07:53.500
What is that?

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:54.725
SPEAKER: Do you want
to tell the group what

00:07:54.725 --> 00:07:55.250
a stage manager does?

00:07:55.250 --> 00:07:56.083
STACEY ZALOGA: Yeah.

00:07:56.083 --> 00:07:58.420
So as a stage manager--

00:07:58.420 --> 00:08:00.580
well, for instance,
on "Beautiful"

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:01.720
there are three of us.

00:08:01.720 --> 00:08:04.570
And basically, we
are there every day

00:08:04.570 --> 00:08:07.712
to make sure that the
production basically happens.

00:08:07.712 --> 00:08:09.670
One of us is on stage
left every day, one of us

00:08:09.670 --> 00:08:12.310
is on stage right every
day, and the other one of us

00:08:12.310 --> 00:08:13.770
calls the show.

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:15.520
And by calling the
show, that's basically,

00:08:15.520 --> 00:08:18.370
we have a script of the entire
show with every light cue

00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:21.790
and every scenic move
that happens in the show.

00:08:21.790 --> 00:08:23.800
And any time the
lights change, it's

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:27.160
because we have said lights 36
go, and someone hits a button.

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:28.750
Any time scenery
moves, it's cause

00:08:28.750 --> 00:08:31.927
we put a warn for a switch
in, and flick the switch off,

00:08:31.927 --> 00:08:33.010
and someone takes the cue.

00:08:33.010 --> 00:08:35.350
So in a way, it's kind
of like conducting

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:38.110
the lights and the scenery.

00:08:38.110 --> 00:08:40.890
And we're also responsible for
watching backstage, making sure

00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:43.140
everything's happening the
way it's supposed to happen

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:46.000
and maintaining the safety
of everyone in the show,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.020
and helping to put new
people into the show,

00:08:49.020 --> 00:08:50.770
and understudy rehearsals,
and maintaining

00:08:50.770 --> 00:08:52.910
the production on a whole.

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:56.080
And we kind of communicate
with every department that's

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:58.100
involved in a production.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:01.646
And our tasks vary from
beginning a show, rehearsals,

00:09:01.646 --> 00:09:03.770
through tech, through
actually running of the show.

00:09:03.770 --> 00:09:07.900
But we're there every
single day doing that.

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:08.400
So yeah.

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:10.900
So when my professor
told me, you'd

00:09:10.900 --> 00:09:12.730
make a great stage
manager, I didn't

00:09:12.730 --> 00:09:13.950
know any of this, of course.

00:09:13.950 --> 00:09:16.490
And I had to learn, in
college, what it was.

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:19.270
And they just kind of threw me
on some main stage productions.

00:09:19.270 --> 00:09:21.700
And it just was
so natural to me.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:26.260
And we didn't actually have a
stage management class there.

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:30.040
So I just was guided
by my professors.

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:32.579
And especially, with
women, there was the chair

00:09:32.579 --> 00:09:35.120
of our department at the time,
[? Gerri ?] [? Maschio, ?] who

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:39.220
was probably the most important
woman in my life as far

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:40.090
as my career goes.

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:45.010
She really guided me along that
process and helped me a lot.

00:09:45.010 --> 00:09:46.927
So she's probably the
most instrumental woman.

00:09:46.927 --> 00:09:48.134
SPEAKER: That's really great.

00:09:48.134 --> 00:09:48.850
I think we all--

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:50.350
especially as women,
in our careers,

00:09:50.350 --> 00:09:52.240
our mentors and our
sponsors are really

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:55.180
pivotal in helping us
find our career path

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:56.590
and taking that next step.

00:09:56.590 --> 00:09:59.530
So coming back to the
show, "Beautiful,"

00:09:59.530 --> 00:10:02.824
it is centered on one
woman's story and career.

00:10:02.824 --> 00:10:04.240
So can you tell
me how each of you

00:10:04.240 --> 00:10:09.026
feel connected to Carole King's
story and her body of work?

00:10:09.026 --> 00:10:10.002
MELISSA BENOIST: Hm.

00:10:10.002 --> 00:10:11.470
[CHUCKLING]

00:10:11.470 --> 00:10:13.750
JOYCE CHITTICK:
Well, I'll start.

00:10:13.750 --> 00:10:16.690
Unlike Stacey, I wasn't here
from the very beginning.

00:10:16.690 --> 00:10:20.020
I came in when we began
the national tour.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:24.540
And I've since gone on and put
together "The Japan Company."

00:10:24.540 --> 00:10:27.220
And now you said
Tony and Grammy,

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:28.930
it's now also a
Helpmann Award winner.

00:10:28.930 --> 00:10:29.680
SPEAKER: Oh, yeah.

00:10:29.680 --> 00:10:30.555
In Australia.

00:10:30.555 --> 00:10:32.180
JOYCE CHITTICK: So
just the other day--

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:35.830
yes, five Tony awards,
including Best Musical.

00:10:35.830 --> 00:10:36.610
So I was there.

00:10:36.610 --> 00:10:40.840
I helped Marc Bruni put together
the production in Australia.

00:10:40.840 --> 00:10:43.050
So I came on board.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:47.040
And I came to see the show
before I met the choreographer.

00:10:47.040 --> 00:10:49.660
And I came by myself, which
I was really glad I did.

00:10:49.660 --> 00:10:52.780
And I just wept.

00:10:52.780 --> 00:10:59.080
And the first time that my
heart strings were pulled

00:10:59.080 --> 00:11:02.920
was when Carole first
sings "Wonderful."

00:11:02.920 --> 00:11:06.910
And I'm a mother now.

00:11:06.910 --> 00:11:10.090
And having lived
your life a lot--

00:11:10.090 --> 00:11:13.990
relationships, et cetera,
marriage, children, et cetera--

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:16.960
there was so much
that spoke to me

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:20.980
and so many songs
in the show that I

00:11:20.980 --> 00:11:24.310
didn't realize that she wrote.

00:11:24.310 --> 00:11:27.910
And they are timeless.

00:11:27.910 --> 00:11:35.030
And I still, three years
later, watch the show,

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:40.385
and I get teary eyed moments
because it's just human nature,

00:11:40.385 --> 00:11:41.260
you know what I mean?

00:11:41.260 --> 00:11:44.020
And there's so
much joy and heart.

00:11:44.020 --> 00:11:49.330
And it speaks to everybody.

00:11:49.330 --> 00:11:50.200
It really does.

00:11:50.200 --> 00:11:52.764
And I was just
instantly drawn to it.

00:11:52.764 --> 00:11:53.680
MELISSA BENOIST: Yeah.

00:11:53.680 --> 00:11:58.150
I had a very similar experience
watching it for the first time.

00:11:58.150 --> 00:12:01.870
I hadn't seen it until I knew
I was going to be doing it.

00:12:01.870 --> 00:12:04.240
So I watched it
for the first time

00:12:04.240 --> 00:12:07.180
the night before I
started rehearsing.

00:12:07.180 --> 00:12:09.160
And I just gave myself
one night to let

00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:10.760
it kind of wash all over me.

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:14.670
And I, essentially, like
washed myself with my tears.

00:12:14.670 --> 00:12:15.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:15.270 --> 00:12:16.440
I was crying.

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:17.540
I was weeping.

00:12:17.540 --> 00:12:18.750
JOYCE CHITTICK: Yeah.

00:12:18.750 --> 00:12:19.690
And in a good way too.

00:12:19.690 --> 00:12:20.565
MELISSA BENOIST: Yes.

00:12:20.565 --> 00:12:25.650
JOYCE CHITTICK: At the end, like
in such a joyful way, the lyric

00:12:25.650 --> 00:12:27.030
that you get to
sing every night,

